out 1141":"circa 1141","Of, Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England":"Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bolton upon Dane, Upon Dearne,Yorkshire,England":"Yorkshire, England","Ormesby, Yorkshire, England":"Ormesby, Yorkshire, England","Kildale, Yorkshire, England":"Kildale, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1095–before 1170":"about 1095–before 1170","1091–Male":"1091–Deceased","1095–1170":"1095–1170","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1141–1204":"1141–1204","1036–1125":"1036–1125","1053–Female":"1053–Deceased","1091":"1091","about 1140":"about 1140","about 1095":"about 1095","1053":"1053","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1204":"1204","1125":"1125","1036":"1036","about 1127":"about 1127","ABT     1088":"about 1088","1100":"1100","before 1170":"before 1170","about 1141":"about 1141","Of, Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England":"Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Bolton upon Dane, Upon Dearne,Yorkshire,England":"Yorkshire, England","Ormesby, Yorkshire, England":"Ormesby, Yorkshire, England","Kildale, Yorkshire, England":"Kildale, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Percy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","nickname from Old French <i>percehaie</i> ‘pierce hedge’ (Old French <i>percer</i> ‘to pierce, penetrate’ + <i>haie</i> ‘hedge, fence’), perhaps with the sense of someone breaking into an enclosure. <i>Percehaie</i> is the name of one of the sons of the foxes Renart and Hermeline in the medieval French epic <i>Roman de Renart</i>, whose earliest known version is from the 1170s. The surname is older than that, but it may originate in a nickname for the fox as ‘enclosure piercer’, perhaps amounting to ‘chicken thief’.","habitational name from any of several places called Percy in Calvados, Eure, and Manche; William <i>de Perci</i>, the Domesday tenant-in-chief and under-tenant of Hugh, Earl of Chester, came from either Percy-en-Auge (Eure) or Percy (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Piercey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Piercy","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcey","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Peercy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]},{"name":"Pearcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Percy  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":1,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":11,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Percy was born about 1095, in Kildale, Yorkshire, England, his father, Picot de Percy, was 61 and his mother, Agnes Alice De St Quintin, was 44. He married Agnes of Yorkshire about 1127, in Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1170, in Ormesby, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1095–before 1170":"umbes 1095–enne 1170","1091–Male":"1091–Surnud","1095–1170":"1095–1170","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1141–1204":"1141–1204","1036–1125":"1036–1125","1053–Female":"1053–Surnud","1091":"1091","about 1140":"umbes 1140","about 1095":"umbes 1095","1053":"1053","1141":"1141","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1204":"1204","1125":"1125","1036":"1036","about 1127":"umbes 1127","ABT     1088":"umbes 1088","1100":"1100","before 1170":"enne 1170","about 1141":"umbes 1141","Of, Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, England":"Bolton Percy, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bolton upon Dane, Upon Dearne,Yorkshire,England":"Yorkshire, Englan